{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3134738,"name":"Jack R","username":"Jack_1221","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/jack_1221/{size}/135876_2.png","created_at":"2023-01-27T04:18:01.691Z","cooked":"<p>Hello All,</p>
<p>Our team just tested our KOP drivetrain w/ NEOs and found that it curves right over time (about 6 inches off center over 15 feet).  The code is giving the same exact speed to both sides, nevertheless this happens.  We dont see any hardware issues, but we will take a deep dive Saturday.  Even unloaded the left drive runs a little faster then the right drive (10 rpm faster).</p>
<p>My question involves possible solutions.  Should we try to program up closed loop velocity control on the Spark Max?  Then our joysticks could set velocities.  Or we could go simpler with an input offset?  This way our autonomous isnt ever under threat of being messed up by code changes.</p>
<p>However, I do not see many teams needing this for a KOP tank drive.  I assumed the internal encoders could take care of everything needed to get an accurate speed from just the <code>.set()</code> method.  Could anyone lend some wisdom on where to start on solving this issue?</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2023-01-27T04:20:33.356Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":91,"reads":287,"readers_count":286,"score":512.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":424816,"topic_slug":"robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions","display_username":"Jack R","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":43292,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions/424816/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true,"can_vote":false},{"id":3134743,"name":"Sean B","username":"Phlogiston","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/phlogiston/{size}/180763_2.png","created_at":"2023-01-27T04:38:49.947Z","cooked":"<p>When you call the “set” method, you are just setting the relative power to the motors - there is no built in feedback, any change in load affects motor speed.  So any tiny difference in friction between the halves of your drivetrain will add up quickly. You don’t necessarily the closed loop control to be on the drive motors; the easiest way to drive consistently in auto is to use a gyro to monitor the robot’s heading and a PID controller to steer the robot straight. You will also need some way of monitoring your encoders to make the robot drive the right distance - timing based autos have major problems with changes in battery voltage and mechanical wear.</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2023-01-27T04:44:52.472Z","reply_count":2,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":266,"readers_count":265,"score":183.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":424816,"topic_slug":"robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions","display_username":"Sean B","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":8}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":44845,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Lone Coder"},"post_url":"/t/robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions/424816/2","custom_user_title":"Lone Coder","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":6},{"id":"point_up","type":"emoji","count":2}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":8,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3134744,"name":"Fletch","username":"Fletch1373","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/fletch1373/{size}/220073_2.png","created_at":"2023-01-27T04:42:50.691Z","cooked":"<p>Slight nitpick, but PID <em><strong>is</strong></em> closed-loop.  But i would agree that it shouldn’t be on the individual drive motors.</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2023-01-27T04:42:50.691Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":243,"readers_count":242,"score":108.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":424816,"topic_slug":"robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions","display_username":"Fletch","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":44845,"username":"Phlogiston","name":"Sean B","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/phlogiston/{size}/180763_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":4}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":9105,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"3181/3015 Mentor | 213/1373 Alum | CSA/FTAA/Jack-of-all-Trades"},"post_url":"/t/robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions/424816/3","custom_user_title":"3181/3015 Mentor | 213/1373 Alum | CSA/FTAA/Jack-of-all-Trades","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":4}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":4,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3134752,"name":"Jack R","username":"Jack_1221","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/jack_1221/{size}/135876_2.png","created_at":"2023-01-27T05:00:11.467Z","cooked":"<p>I am pretty sure the auto wpilib implementation takes care of that by basing speed on distance traveled.  So really this issue is a problem in teleop getting joystick input.  There is no set distance/velocity so I really dont know how to approach closed loop without creating a whole scale just for translating joystick to velocities.</p>
<p>Edit:  I realize my original post didnt clarify that so far our auto seems to cope with the curve.  We are using a RamseteCommand.  I am primarily asking for <strong>teleop</strong> as I am unsure if PID loops for velocity are needed instead of <code>set()</code>.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2023-01-27T05:02:58.895Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":228,"readers_count":227,"score":50.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":424816,"topic_slug":"robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions","display_username":"Jack R","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":44845,"username":"Phlogiston","name":"Sean B","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/phlogiston/{size}/180763_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":43292,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions/424816/4","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3134757,"name":"UnofficialForth","username":"UnofficialForth","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/unofficialforth/{size}/167902_2.png","created_at":"2023-01-27T05:11:25.706Z","cooked":"<p>In all the times I’ve seen a robot curve to the right majorly, it was because something wasn’t exactly put together right. There might be a collision, or rubbing, or something. In the long run, pulling it apart and inspecting to make sure both sides are even is much less of a bandage fix than software. You have time, see if you can figure out what’s wrong.</p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2023-01-27T05:11:25.706Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":205,"readers_count":204,"score":51.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":424816,"topic_slug":"robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions","display_username":"UnofficialForth","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":2}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":29982,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"FRC Team 4272  Mentor | World's FLL Emcee"},"post_url":"/t/robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions/424816/5","custom_user_title":"FRC Team 4272  Mentor | World's FLL Emcee","reactions":[{"id":"point_up","type":"emoji","count":2}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":2,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3134758,"name":"","username":"Akash_Rastogi","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/akash_rastogi/{size}/169937_2.png","created_at":"2023-01-27T05:12:20.949Z","cooked":"<p>Yeah even if this is compensated for in software, you should check the transmission on the slower side for over tightening, lack of lubrication, etc.</p>","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2023-01-27T05:12:20.949Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":5,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":188,"readers_count":187,"score":37.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":424816,"topic_slug":"robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":29982,"username":"UnofficialForth","name":"UnofficialForth","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/unofficialforth/{size}/167902_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":8002,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"177 & 429 | #TeamWCP| #TeamThrifty"},"post_url":"/t/robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions/424816/6","custom_user_title":"177 & 429 | #TeamWCP| #TeamThrifty","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3134761,"name":"Sean B","username":"Phlogiston","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/phlogiston/{size}/180763_2.png","created_at":"2023-01-27T05:18:04.870Z","cooked":"<p>OH i’m sorry I didn’t understand! As <a class="mention" href="/u/unofficialforth">@UnofficialForth</a> said, start by figuring out hardware issues. But just in case you still were to decide you want velocity-based driving, you can certainly do it. Here’s what it looks like:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">SimpleMotorFeedforward feedforward = new SimpleMotorFeedforward(kS, kV, kA);
PIDController leftController = new PIDController(kP, kI, kD);
PIDController rightController = new PIDController(kP, kI, kD);
public void velocityDrive(DifferentialDriveWheelSpeeds speeds, DifferentialDriveWheelSpeeds previousSpeeds, double dt){
    double leftFeedforward, rightFeedforward, left, right;

    leftFeedforward = feedforward.calculate(
      speeds.leftMetersPerSecond,
      (speeds.leftMetersPerSecond - previousSpeeds.leftMetersPerSecond) / dt
    );

    rightFeedforward = feedforward.calculate(
      speeds.rightMetersPerSecond,
      (speeds.rightMetersPerSecond - previousSpeeds.rightMetersPerSecond) / dt
    );

    left = leftFeedforward + leftController.calculate(
            getWheelSpeeds().leftMetersPerSecond, speeds.leftMetersPerSecond
    );
    right = rightFeedforward + rightController.calculate(
            getWheelSpeeds().rightMetersPerSecond, speeds.rightMetersPerSecond
    );

    tankDriveVolts(left, right);
  }
</code></pre>
<p>(I wrote a velocity drive mode so I could test how well our velocity gains were working without needing to worry about issues with path following) If you do decide you want this, then I’d recommend putting some filters on your joystick input to because it is <em>very</em> sensitive. I’d recommend getting your drivetrain assembled as perfectly as possible first, though. You really don’t need this.</p>","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2023-01-27T05:18:04.870Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":173,"readers_count":172,"score":44.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":424816,"topic_slug":"robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions","display_username":"Sean B","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":43292,"username":"Jack_1221","name":"Jack R","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/jack_1221/{size}/135876_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":44845,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Lone Coder"},"post_url":"/t/robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions/424816/7","custom_user_title":"Lone Coder","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3134845,"name":"philso","username":"philso","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/p/e68b1a/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-01-27T14:21:02.248Z","cooked":"<p>Do the  following  tests.</p>
<p>With the battery disconnected and the chassis propped up so that the wheels don’t touch the ground, spin the wheels to see if one side has more resistance than the other.</p>
<p>Disconnect one motor on each side and run it. Reconnect the motors then disconnect the second motor on each side and run it.</p>
<p>Swap the connections so that the controllers for the right side are driving the motors on the left and the controllers for the left side are driving the motors on the right.</p>
<p>Remove the motors and check that the gears installed on them all have the same number of teeth.</p>","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2023-01-27T14:21:02.248Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":133,"readers_count":132,"score":61.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":424816,"topic_slug":"robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions","display_username":"philso","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":2}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":15467,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions/424816/8","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":2}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":2,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3134856,"name":"Clayton Colburn","username":"Clayton_Colburn","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/c/ccd318/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-01-27T14:36:24.029Z","cooked":"<p>I would also recommend calibrating the speed controllers and your joysticks. Sometimes that can fix any discrepancy between the two sides.</p>","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2023-01-27T14:36:24.029Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":126,"readers_count":125,"score":25.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":424816,"topic_slug":"robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions","display_username":"Clayton Colburn","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":34129,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/robot-curves-when-its-supposed-to-drive-straight-hardware-or-mechanical-solutions/424816/9","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3134877,"name":"Mike Taylor (he/him)","username":"Taylor","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/taylor/{size}/232955_2.png","created_at":"2023-01-27T15:47:59.147Z","cooked":"<p>A couple seasons ago, we fought this same thing for months.  Long story short, one of the pinions on our drive motor was 16T while all the others were 15T.<br>
